Author: (Montagu, 1808)
Notes: Dr. Leslie Harris, polychaete expert, remarks: "different NEP websites & publications report this soft-sediment worm as both M. infundibulum and M. aesthetica, which is the first part of the confusion. In Europe M. infundibulum is found in soft-sediments & M. aesthetica is the one hanging from docks & hard-surfaces so if our NEP specimens are really the same as an european species they would be M. infundibulum. However, our NEP specimens are distinctly different both morphologically & genetically from infundibulum. The second part of the confusion is what to call them. In the past several NEP species of Myxicola were described from California, Puget Sound, and Alaska. All of the original specimens need to be re-examined so we can decide what name (or names) to use in the NEP."

Author: (Stephens)
Notes: "Chrysoperla carnea does not occur in North America. It is a European member of a sibling species complex that contains several other species in North America. Some of the members of this complex are only differentiable on the basis of 'songs' (abdominal tremulation patterns), and are not distinguishable on any known morphological grounds." (J.D. Oswald)
